rritorial acquisitions from this perspective. They find that at least one American acquisition of territory and many of the basic institutions of territorial governance have no constitutional foundation, and they explore the often-strange paths that constitutional law has traveled to permit such deviations from the Constitution's original meaning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aConstitutional historyxUnited States. 0aConstitutional historyzUnited States. 0aConstitutional lawxUnited States. 0aConstitutional lawzUnited States. 0aDroit constitutionnelxÉtats-Unis. 0aImperialismxHistory. 0aImpérialismexHistoire. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh1 aSeidman, Guy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300128963423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300128963.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles